<div id="review_3223240647" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3223240647" />
    <a title="Meike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59050228-meike"><img alt="Meike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1634545742p2/59050228.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3223240647?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Meike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Meike" href="/user/show/59050228-meike">Meike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59050228-meike?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59050228-meike?shelf=2020-read">2020-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3223240647" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8828671454369863918">This is more of an epic poem than a novel: Written like a symphony of cumulative voices rendered in a &quot;we&quot; form, Otsuka tells the stories of Japanese girls and women who came to the US in the early 1900s as so-called &quot;picture brides&quot;. This practice entailed that matchmakers paired brides and grooms on different sides of the Pacific solely based on pictures, letters and family recommendations, meaning that girls and women went to the States to marry Japanese immigrant men they had never met in re</span>
  <span id="freeText8828671454369863918" style="display:none">This is more of an epic poem than a novel: Written like a symphony of cumulative voices rendered in a "we" form, Otsuka tells the stories of Japanese girls and women who came to the US in the early 1900s as so-called "picture brides". This practice entailed that matchmakers paired brides and grooms on different sides of the Pacific solely based on pictures, letters and family recommendations, meaning that girls and women went to the States to marry Japanese immigrant men they had never met in real life. The short text starts during such a passage, describing the expectations and fears of the future brides, it takes the reader through the first encounter with their new husbands (mostly linked to dire disappointment), talks about the hard work on fields, as housekeepers, in brothels and in factories, the love affairs and children up to the internment of the Japanese/Japanese-Americans (both citizens and non-citizens) during WW II. <br /><br />The different experiences Otsuka encompasses in her story are offered in enumerative descriptions, frequently structured with the help of anaphors, thus adding various angles and developments depending on coincidence and personal decisions. It is this lyrical choice that makes the novel unique, but that also requires intense concentration from the reader - there is a lot to process, and while the book paints a wide panorama, it is not particularly immersive as it does not stick to indvidual characters or a clear storyline (or, in fact, any storyline at all). <br /><br />This book needs to be appreciated as poetry, as a text that offers emotional insights, and the twist at the end is extremely effective. The title-giving Buddha in the attic is a little brass statuette a Japanese woman leaves behind after being deported to an internment camp - the book is full of such strong, poetic images. Not an easy read, but a worthwhile one. <br /><br />(Also available in German: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15822310.Wovon_wir_tr_umten" title="Wovon wir träumten by Julie Otsuka" rel="nofollow noopener">Wovon wir träumten</a>)</span>
  <a data-text-id="8828671454369863918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


