  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3715253956" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3715253956" />
    <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler"><img alt="Clif Hostetler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593302055p2/793473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3715253956?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clif Hostetler" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler">Clif Hostetler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/793473-clif-hostetler?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3715253956" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6006609443349898114">This historical novel tells the Japanese American story beginning with the viewpoint of &quot;<a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picture_bride' rel='nofollow noopener'>picture brides</a>&quot; who came to California in the early 20th century all told in the first person plural &quot;we&quot; tense. In subsequent chapters other aspects of Japanese immigrant life—sex, employment, children—are explored continuing to use the technique of <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anaphora_(rhetoric)' rel='nofollow noopener'>anaphora</a> as a means to communicate the breath and variety of experiences by repeating sentences beginning with &quot;We did …&quot; or &quot;Some of us …&quot;. In the chapter abou</span>
  <span id="freeText6006609443349898114" style="display:none">This historical novel tells the Japanese American story beginning with the viewpoint of "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picture_bride" rel="nofollow noopener">picture brides</a>" who came to California in the early 20th century all told in the first person plural "we" tense. In subsequent chapters other aspects of Japanese immigrant life—sex, employment, children—are explored continuing to use the technique of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anaphora_(rhetoric)" rel="nofollow noopener">anaphora</a> as a means to communicate the breath and variety of experiences by repeating sentences beginning with "We did …" or "Some of us …". In the chapter about their children the narrative switches to repeating "Some of them …" to show the variety of ways in which their children often were ashamed of their broken English and foreign ways. <br /><br />Their experiences may have been varied but when WWII arrived their adopted country considered them to be a monolithic threat to national security and quickly gathered them together to be sent off to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internment_of_Japanese_Americans" rel="nofollow noopener">internment camps</a>. Then before the reader realizes the switch the book's narrative voice continues in the first person plural "we," but now it is the voice of their Anglo neighbors, acquaintances and school mates who at first miss them, then get use to their absence, and then forget about them. <br /><br />In some ways this story has many similarities to other immigrant groups with a beginning filled with hard times and hard work. But the ending of this story with the internment camps is poignantly unique to Japanese Americans. It was an obvious mistake in American history that provides haunting reminders of the Native American and African American experiences which are also examples of failure to live up to the American ideal of justice, equality, and freedom.<br /><br />In case you're wondering about the book's title, it is mentioned near the end of the book when they are leaving their homes for the internment camps. <blockquote>"Haruko left a tiny laughing brass Buddha up high, in a corner of the attic, where he is still laughing to this day.”</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="6006609443349898114" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


